      {
        "id": "c339f495f28abaf05d48e5e468393c785ede737a",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 741,
          "name": "Kanagaraj Manickam",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "kanagaraj.manickam@huawei.com",
          "username": "mkr1481"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-10-23 02:33:18.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\nI feel this is not right approach to generate the doc, because ocomp used by vtp already provides feature to get these rules details as given below commad\nocomp --product open-cli schema-list --product onap-dublin --service  vnf-compliance --format json\nif format is skiped, by default it provides in table format\n\nI suggest to use this approach and if required add support for generating the output in rst table format as new feature in ocomp (cli project), \n\nLet me know if any further help required?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "ecbbae6e363e13393c4b8e4c3dc4f9b696e4d077",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5098,
          "name": "Bartosz Gardziejewski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "bartosz.gardziejewski@nokia.com",
          "username": "BartoszG"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-10-23 08:29:44.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n> \n> I feel this is not right approach to generate the doc, because ocomp used by vtp already provides feature to get these rules details as given below commad\n> ocomp --product open-cli schema-list --product onap-dublin --service  vnf-compliance --format json\n> if format is skiped, by default it provides in table format\n> \n> I suggest to use this approach and if required add support for generating the output in rst table format as new feature in ocomp (cli project), \n> \n> Let me know if any further help required?\n\nIf I understand You correctly, You mean oclip command:\noclip --product open-cli schema-list --product onap-dublin --service  vnf-compliance\nAlthough in order to perform this command we need running oclip container or using oclip wrapper, like in tests. Both of those approaches may be misleading, because we would have to use properties files that contains rules and descriptions, in order to configure oclip, then we would get them back from oclip in order to create table for documentation, if I understand correctly, how olcip works in that case. I thing that using files with rules and descriptions directly to generate tables for documentation is more readable, straightforward and moreover less prone to bugs and errors that may be caused by oclip and from vnfsdk point of view oclip it outside library. That is why we think that using simple script to reorganize data that we already have, instead of using outside library is better idea. If I am missing your point or if there is other way to use oclip in that case please let me know.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "24c33cc0d5bfb95844231d74bd6281755e2a405f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 741,
          "name": "Kanagaraj Manickam",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "kanagaraj.manickam@huawei.com",
          "username": "mkr1481"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-10-29 02:42:07.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2\n\n> Patch Set 4:\n> \n> > Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n> > \n> > I feel this is not right approach to generate the doc, because ocomp used by vtp already provides feature to get these rules details as given below commad\n> > ocomp --product open-cli schema-list --product onap-dublin --service  vnf-compliance --format json\n> > if format is skiped, by default it provides in table format\n> > \n> > I suggest to use this approach and if required add support for generating the output in rst table format as new feature in ocomp (cli project), \n> > \n> > Let me know if any further help required?\n> \n> If I understand You correctly, You mean oclip command:\n> oclip --product open-cli schema-list --product onap-dublin --service  vnf-compliance\n> Although in order to perform this command we need running oclip container or using oclip wrapper, like in tests. Both of those approaches may be misleading, because we would have to use properties files that contains rules and descriptions, in order to configure oclip, then we would get them back from oclip in order to create table for documentation, if I understand correctly, how olcip works in that case. I thing that using files with rules and descriptions directly to generate tables for documentation is more readable, straightforward and moreover less prone to bugs and errors that may be caused by oclip and from vnfsdk point of view oclip it outside library. That is why we think that using simple script to reorganize data that we already have, instead of using outside library is better idea. If I am missing your point or if there is other way to use oclip in that case please let me know.\n\nok considering your input, its  your approach is directly helping to solve the purpose and its good, but as we are depending on the YAML file format supported by oclip and it provides the way to generate the report, it would be right approach for generating the report. logically its better to go with YAML parser (oclip) and use it for generating the repo. I am ok.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
